[2] Spanish cucumbers cleared as vehicle
Date: Tue 31 May 2011
Source: FreshPlaza [edited]
http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=81284


Spanish cucumbers are not the source of the _E. coli_ O104 outbreak.
This has been released by Hamburg senator Cornelia Prufer-Storcks this
afternoon, 31 May 2011. A bacterium has been found, but not of the
type O104, which led to the outbreak of _E. coli_, which at the time
of publishing already has resulted in the death of 16 people.

Richard Soepenberg from Frunet Bio isn't surprised by this
afternoon's statement. "We always assumed it. Tests on our cucumbers
have always been negative." Frunet Bio is still not officially
indicted. "We have received a 2nd opinion, which was also negative and
thus positive for us. We never received documents to say we were the
source. I have always been convinced that the cucumbers had nothing to
do with us. Our customers are mainly in the French market, which is
good for 60 percent of our volume, and no one has become sick over
there. The cause of the source must be sought, in my opinion, in
Northern Germany."

Tuesday afternoon, 31 May 2011, it was also made known that the EHEC
[enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_] bacterium has not been found in Dutch
vegetables. This is according to results of a study commissioned by
the Productschap Tuinbouw. According to a spokesperson, several
samples were tested from Dutch cucumbers, tomatoes, lettuce and
peppers. The EHEC bacterium was not found.

[Byline: Sander Bruins Slot]

--
