[5] USA
Date: Tue 31 May 2011
Source: msnbc.com [edited]
http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/43227702/ns/health-infectious_diseases/


Federal health officials confirmed Tue 31 May 2011 that 2 USA
residents who recently traveled in northern Germany appear to be among
victims of a massive outbreak of food poisoning that has killed 16 and
sickened more than 1150 people in Europe since the 2nd week of May
2011 [week of 9 May 2011].

The victims have been hospitalized with serious, life-threatening
complications of _E. coli_ infections caused by a rare strain of the
bacterium that has taken scientists by surprise, said Dr Robert Tauxe,
deputy director of foodborne, bacterial, and mycotic diseases at the
CDC.

"We have never seen that organism before," Tauxe told msnbc.com. He's
referring to _E. coli_ O104:H4, a strain that can cause many of the
problems of the better-known _E. coli_ O157:H7, including bloody
diarrhea and the potentially deadly hemolytic uremic syndrome, or
HUS.

The American victims, who have not been identified by name, state, or
geography, were reported by state health officials who are monitoring
illness surveillance systems for signs that the outbreak has made its
way from Europe to America. Investigation of their cases is
continuing, Tauxe said.

State health agencies have been directed to report instances of HUS
or bloody diarrhea in recent travelers to Germany. Meantime, officials
with the FDA say they're flagging cucumbers, lettuce and tomatoes from
Spanish growers implicated in the outbreak for further inspection.
"Luckily, this is not a huge import season for vegetables," said
Siobhan DeLancey, an FDA spokeswoman.

Tauxe and other food safety experts said they would expect cases to
expand beyond Germany and 8 other European nations to the USA. "It's
hard for me to believe there won't be a handful of travelers who ate
contaminated food in a restaurant," said Dr Dennis Maki, an infectious
disease expert and professor emeritus at the University of Wisconsin
Department of Medicine. "I'll be surprised if we don't have a few
cases."

The rare germ, which is a type of bacterium known as Shiga-toxin
producing _E. coli_, or STEC, appears to be resistant to many commonly
used antibiotics, said Tauxe. However, doctors typically try to stay
away from antibiotics in STEC cases. Because HUS causes kidney failure
and acute anemia, victims are typically treated with dialysis and
other emergency measures.

It's not yet clear whether this strain of _E. coli_ is more virulent
than others, or whether there are massive numbers of milder cases that
have gone undetected, Tauxe added.

Germany's top health official said 373 people [now 470 -- see [1]
above] have come down with HUS, in which _E. coli_ [toxin] attacks the
kidneys, often requiring critical care. Another 796 people in the
country have been hit by less serious infection with the _E. coli_.
The northern city of Hamburg and surrounding areas have been worst
affected. In a typical year, Germany might see 60 cases of HUS,
officials said.

Investigators in Europe continued to scramble Tue 31 May 2011, to
detect the source of the unprecedented outbreak that has been tied to
raw cucumbers, lettuce or tomatoes. European Union officials said
Germany identified cucumbers from the Spanish regions of Almeria and
Malaga as possible sources of contamination. [But the contaminant from
Spain was a different strain -- see [2] above].

Another suspect batch may have originated in the Netherlands or
Denmark. The vegetables could have been contaminated at any point on
the journey from field to retail outlets.

Though FDA officials are flagging incoming produce from Spain for
infection, they don't expect huge quantities of vegetables. In all of
May 2011, for instance, the USA imported one shipment of Spanish
cucumbers, or 480 cases. So far, there is no indication that the
shipment was contaminated, DeLancey said.

The vast majority of _E. coli_ infections have affected either
Germans or people who recently traveled to Germany. Other
[Germany-related] cases have been reported in Denmark, France, the
Czech Republic, the UK, the Netherlands, and Switzerland but the WHO
said it only had confirmation of the German cases and another 6 cases
in France.

[Byline: JoNel Aleccia]

--
